  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A local price peak where a candle's high is greater than those of its immediate neighbors, confirmed only after a lower high forms to its right. It marks buy-side liquidity (stop orders), defines market structure, and serves as an anchor for Fibonacci retracement ranges (premium/discount). Its sweep with aggressive displacement below signals a bearish market structure shift.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Locate a candle whose high is greater than the highs of the candles immediately to its left and right on the chosen time frame.",
    "Wait for a lower high to form to the right of the candidate high; only then is the swing high confirmed.",
    "For reversal/reference purposes, confirm the swing high is swept (price trades above it) and then validated by a close below the series of up-close candles that formed it (a change in state of delivery); if it does not close below, it is not considered a confirmed swing high.",
    "Classify swing highs by structural significance: short-term (simple peak), intermediate-term (short-term highs on either side), or long-term (formed off a higher time frame reaction).",
    "Distinguish relevant swing highs from failure swings: a high left untaken during a directional move is a failure swing and is treated as a liquidity target, not a reversal point.",
    "When two or more swing highs form at similar levels with little separation, treat them as a single equal highs liquidity cluster.",
    "For Fibonacci range analysis, identify the most prominent peak in the price section; pair it with a corresponding swing low; if a new higher swing high prints, update the range anchor.",
    "Validate significance by checking that the swing high lies within a higher time frame point of interest (e.g., fair value gap, previous day high, order block).",
    "In the context of liquidity sweeps, ensure the swing high has not yet been traded through; a sweep must involve a break above followed by displacement back inside the range; a consolidation that merely approaches but does not pierce the high is not a sweep.",
    "In an uptrend, subsequent swing highs should be higher (higher high); in a downtrend, subsequent swing highs should be lower (lower high).",
    "When price continuously makes new highs, update the swing high mark to track the expanding range."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Swing highs serve as buy-side liquidity pools, providing targets for upside sweeps before reversals or continuation moves. In a bearish context, a sweep and subsequent displacement below the swing high confirms a market structure shift, setting up short entries with stops above the high. For range analysis, swing highs anchor Fibonacci retracement to define premium zones for selling. Unswept swing highs act as upside draw on liquidity for bullish continuations. They also validate order block and fair value gap entries. After a sweep, if price fails to close above the high (failure to displace), expect a bearish move toward sell-side liquidity.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering a short after a swing high sweep without a confirmed close below the up-close candles (change in state of delivery).",
    "Trading a swing high reversal without higher time frame point of interest confluence.",
    "Treating any local peak as a significant swing high instead of focusing on prominent, structurally relevant highs.",
    "Not updating the swing high anchor when price prints a new higher high.",
    "Misidentifying internal range liquidity (fair value gaps) as external range liquidity (swing highs).",
    "Assuming a consolidation that merely approaches the swing high constitutes a sweep.",
    "Placing stops at the order block level rather than above the swing high.",
    "Attempting a reversal short without an inversion fair value gap or clear displacement.",
    "Believing every sweep of a swing high signals reversal, overlooking continuation scenarios.",
    "Ignoring multiple swing highs with significant separation, marking only one target.",
    "Not waiting for the right-side lower high to close before confirming the swing high, leading to premature labeling.",
    "Assuming price reversal upon touching the swing high without waiting for a close above or below.",
    "Labeling every local peak as a swing high without strict structural conditions.",
    "Confusing liquidity sweeps within a range with structural swing highs.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe bias, shorting at a swing high in an uptrend.",
    "Failing to update swing high marks when price makes new highs."
  ],
